  <rdf:Description rdf:nodeID="n77c2a26f99c94a33993b8edf520dd96cb834">
    <rdf:type rdf:resource="http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#Restriction"/>
    <owl:someValuesFrom rdf:resource="https://www.inf.ufrgs.br/ontologies/copi/OutletConnection"/>
    <owl:onProperty rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/hasComponentPartAtAllTimes"/>
  </rdf:Description>
  <rdf:Description rdf:about="https://www.inf.ufrgs.br/ontologies/copi/COPI_0000120">
    <rdfs:label xml:lang="pt-br">válvula gaveta</rdfs:label>
    <rdfs:label xml:lang="en">gate valve</rdfs:label>
    <skos:definition xml:lang="en">[SLB Glossary] A type of valve that incorporates a sliding gate to block fluid flow.</skos:definition>
    <skos:definition xml:lang="en">[POSC Caesar] A valve that is a valve where the closure member is a gate or disc with a linear motion parallel, or nearly parallel, to the plane of flat seats, which are transverse to the direction of flow.</skos:definition>
    <skos:definition xml:lang="en">[CFIHOS] A valve that is a valve where the closure member is a gate or disc with a linear motion parallel, or nearly parallel, to the plane of flat seats, which are transverse to the direction of flow.</skos:definition>
    <skos:definition xml:lang="en">[ISO 15926-4] A &lt;GATE VALVE&gt; is an &lt;ARTEFACT&gt; and a &lt;VALVE&gt; that is a valve where the closure member is a gate or disc with a linear motion parallel, or nearly parallel, to the plane of flat seats, which are transverse to the direction of flow</skos:definition>
    <skos:definition xml:lang="en">[OnePetro] A valve with a sliding bar – common in the oilfield as tree valves.                  Gate valve is defined in API SPEC 6A as a valve assembly with a closure mechanism operating within the body, 90° to the conduit, to affect a closure. Gate valves are commonly used in the wellhead section of the well either as a side outlet valve in the spools or in the Christmas tree.                  Gate valves have two modes, either fully open or fully closed. This distinguish the gate valve from the chole valve. The gate valve will allow the fluid to follow or it will completely stop it. On the other hand, a choke valve will restrict the flow.                  Gate valves have several components including but not limited to:                  * Gate                  * Seat                  * Stem                  * Stem Packing (Seal)                  * Bearings                  * Grease fitting                  * Studs and nuts                  * Hand wheel</skos:definition>
    <iof-av:naturalLanguageDefinition xml:lang="pt-br">Uma válvula gaveta é uma válvula que possui um membro de fechamento tipo gaveta ou disco com movimento linear paralelo ao plano dos assentos planos, que são transversais à direção do fluxo.</iof-av:naturalLanguageDefinition>
    <iof-av:naturalLanguageDefinition xml:lang="en">A gate valve is a valve that has a gate or disc closure member with linear motion parallel to the plane of flat seats, which are transverse to the direction of flow.</iof-av:naturalLanguageDefinition>
    <iof-av:isPrimitive rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#boolean">true</iof-av:isPrimitive>
    <rdfs:subClassOf rdf:nodeID="n77c2a26f99c94a33993b8edf520dd96cb1707"/>
    <rdfs:subClassOf rdf:nodeID="n77c2a26f99c94a33993b8edf520dd96cb1708"/>
    <rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="https://www.inf.ufrgs.br/ontologies/copi/COPI_0000077"/>
    <iof-av:firstOrderLogicAxiom xml:lang="en">∀x (GateValve(x) → (Valve(x) ∧ ∃g(GateClosure(g) ∧ hasComponentPartAtAllTimes(x,g)) ∧ ∃m(LinearActuationMechanism(m) ∧ hasComponentPartAtAllTimes(x,m))))</iof-av:firstOrderLogicAxiom>
    <iof-av:primitiveRationale xml:lang="en">Constructive classification based on physical mechanism. Under OWA, defining sufficient conditions for structural features like 'linear sliding gate' risks false positives from complex hybrid equipment or custom manifolds that contain gate mechanisms but should not be classified as standard gate valves. Necessary conditions provide safer classification that can be validated by domain experts.</iof-av:primitiveRationale>
    <rdf:type rdf:resource="http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#Class"/>
    <iof-av:semiFormalNaturalLanguageAxiom xml:lang="en">Every gate valve is a valve that has a gate closure component and a linear actuation mechanism.</iof-av:semiFormalNaturalLanguageAxiom>
  </rdf:Description>
  <rdf:Description rdf:nodeID="n77c2a26f99c94a33993b8edf520dd96cb2781">
    <owl:onProperty rdf:resource="https://spec.industrialontologies.org/ontology/construct/hasComponentPartAtAllTimes"/>
    <rdf:type rdf:resource="http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#Restriction"/>
    <owl:someValuesFrom rdf:resource="https://www.inf.ufrgs.br/ontologies/copi/PumpChamber"/>
  </rdf:Description>
  <rdf:Description rdf:about="https://www.inf.ufrgs.br/ontologies/copi/COPI_0000145">
    <owl:equivalentClass rdf:nodeID="n77c2a26f99c94a33993b8edf520dd96cb2739"/>
    <skos:definition xml:lang="en">[CFIHOS] A self operating valve that is set to open at a certain pressure level to prevent the pressure in a container or system from reaching unsafe levels.</skos:definition>
    <skos:definition xml:lang="en">[SLB Glossary] A quick-acting, spring-loaded valve that opens to relieve pressure when the pressure exceeds the spring setting.</skos:definition>
    <skos:definition xml:lang="en">[POSC Caesar] A self operating valve that is set to open at a certain pressure level to prevent the pressure in a container or system from reaching unsafe levels.</skos:definition>
    <skos:definition xml:lang="en">[ISO 15926-4] A &lt;RELIEF VALVE&gt; is an &lt;INSTRUMENTATION ITEM&gt; and a &lt;PRESSURE RELIEF DEVICE&gt; that is set to open at a certain pressure level to prevent the pressure in a container or system from reaching unsafe levels</skos:definition>
    <skos:definition xml:lang="en">[OnePetro] A valve in a pressurized system that is set to open and relieve pressure at a certain pressure level.</skos:definition>
    <iof-av:naturalLanguageDefinition xml:lang="en">A relief valve is a valve that is designed to automatically open at a predetermined pressure setpoint to relieve excess pressure and prevent unsafe pressure levels in a system.</iof-av:naturalLanguageDefinition>
    <iof-av:naturalLanguageDefinition xml:lang="pt-br">Uma válvula de alívio é uma válvula projetada para abrir automaticamente em um ponto de ajuste de pressão predeterminado para aliviar o excesso de pressão e prevenir níveis de pressão inseguros em um sistema.</iof-av:naturalLanguageDefinition>
    <rdf:type rdf:resource="http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#Class"/>
    <iof-av:semiFormalNaturalLanguageAxiom xml:lang="en">Every relief valve is a valve that bears a pressure relief function, which realizes a pressure relief process that automatically opens the valve when system pressure exceeds a predetermined setpoint.</iof-av:semiFormalNaturalLanguageAxiom>
    <iof-av:firstOrderLogicAxiom xml:lang="en">∀x (ReliefValve(x) ↔ (Valve(x) ∧ ∃f (PressureReliefFunction(f) ∧ bearerOf(x,f))))</iof-av:firstOrderLogicAxiom>
    <rdfs:label xml:lang="pt-br">válvula de alívio</rdfs:label>
    <rdfs:label xml:lang="en">relief valve</rdfs:label>
  </rdf:Description>
